ed form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>: habitational name from Montfoort in Utrecht. It is a cognate of 1 above (see   Monfort   1) and also its altered form (or perhaps vice versa).","English (of Norman origin): very rare variant of   Mountford  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Monfort","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Jacques, Marcel, Monique, Wilner.","French and Breton: habitational name from any of numerous places called Montfort, from Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ (see   Mont   1) + <i>fort</i> ‘strong, impregnable’ (from Latin <i>fortis</i>). This surname is by far most common in Brittany. It is also found in Haiti. Compare   Montfort   1, see also 2 below.","Altered form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>, a variant of   Montfort   2 and also a cognate of the French name in 1 above and an altered form of its variant   Montfort   1 (or perhaps vice versa)."]},{"name":"Monforte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Carmela, Carmine, Rocco, Rosaria, Sal.  Spanish Carlos, Francisco, Luis, Medardo.","Italian and Spanish: habitational name from any of numerous places called Monforte, from Latin <i>mons</i> ‘mountain’ (genitive <i>montis</i>) + <i>fortis</i> ‘strong’, probably a reference to the strategic position of these locations.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Montfort  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Montfort was born about 1285, in Castle, Jackson, South Dakota, United States, her father, John De Montfort Baron Of Beaudesert, was 11283 and her mother, Alicia Plaunche, was 20. She married Bartholomew de Sudeley. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1285–":"umbes 1285–Surnud","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1286–1330":"1286–1330","1288–1326":"1288–1326","1291–1314":"1291–1314","1292–1370":"1292–1370","1275–1327":"1275–1327","1305–1339":"1305–1339","1264–1296":"1264–1296","1267–1309":"1267–1309","1264":"1264","1275":"1275","1330":"1330","1286":"1286","1296":"1296","1285":"1285","12 June 1305":"12. juuni 1305","1370":"1370","1292":"1292","1291":"1291","Abt 1285":"umbes 1285","1305":"1305","1327":"1327","1326":"1326","1314":"1314","before 28 March 1287":"enne 28. märtsi 1287","1267":"1267","1288":"1288","1309":"1309","1339":"1339","Beaudesert Castle &amp; Manor, Henley-in-Arden, Barlichway, nS, Barlichway, South Warwickshire":"Castle, Jackson, Lõuna-Dakota, Ameerika Ühendriigid","Sudeley, Gloucestershire, England":"Sudeley, Gloucestershire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1285–":"noin 1285–Kuollut","1285–Female":"1285–Kuollut","1286–1330":"1286–1330","1288–1326":"1288–1326","1291–1314":"1291–1314","1292–1370":"1292–1370","1275–1327":"1275–1327","1305–1339":"1305–1339","1264–1296":"1264–1296","1267–1309":"1267–1309","1264"